This exercise is included in my “Emotions 101” online course! The course is only available for purchase until May 2nd - so I highly recommend getting on this list. Click the link in my bio to get your spot!

Some disclaimers about these exercises:
- If you have a trauma history, experience flashbacks, have trouble with emotional regulation, experience suicidal ideation, or any other distressing symptoms, I highly recommend and suggest you practice these exercises with a trauma-informed, licensed therapist first.
- If at any point these exercises cause you to feel so overwhelmed or uncomfortable that you cannot continue, stop. Take note of any symptoms of distress: eyes fluttering, becoming hypervigilant, rapid or unsettled body movements, feeling overly uncomfortable, rapid heartbeat, overheating, or any other common signs of emotional flooding you experience.
- Before getting started, you may want to have some grounding items around you. Start in a comfortable space with things that help you remain calm. This may be a blanket, a photo, etc.
- Remember, you are the expert on your body and your experience. If something doesn’t work for you - that’s ok.
- Instead of judging or questioning yourself, try to stay with what is happening in your body. You can ask yourself questions like:
How am I noticing these feelings?
What is my experience like right now?
What is my body experiencing?
What am I wondering about?
What would help me feel safe right now?
- If you are really struggling with being still and reflecting on your internal experience, it may be best to practice mindfulness in other ways - like while eating, taking a shower, etc. to practice.

node.text:
Back in my office @thecollaborativemiami today and thought I’d record my first IGTV video ever! Tackling the questions: Why do people stay in bad relationships?

Let’s talk about why it’s so hard to “just leave.”

Disclaimer: If you are being abused, emotionally or physically, you are not at fault. If the abuse is still going on and the other person has not made a deliberate effort to seek help and/or change their behavior, the relationship is not safe. These other signs are not possible until the abuse has stopped and the abuser takes responsibility for their actions and their role. I’m going to include some available resources in the caption of this video.

Leaving a toxic relationship can also be dangerous. I know most of us don’t think it would happen to us, but there are millions of reported cases of domestic violence a year in the US. Remember that your safety is most important. Here are some resources I recommend:
* Find a therapist in your area that specializes in abusive relationships.
* Support groups:
 Adult Children of Alcoholics
 ALANON
 Trauma Survivor Groups
 Domestic Violence Support Groups
* National Domestic Violence Hotline: 800-799-SAFE
* Books
 Gaslighting - Stephanie Sarkis
 The Gaslight Effect - Robin Stern
 Adult Children of Emotionally Immature Parents - Lindsey Gibson
* Domesticshelters.org has a lot of resources and book suggestions

PS. it’s EMAIL DAY! Make sure to vote for the topic in my stories and swipe up to get on my email list.

node.title: Why People Stay In Bad Relationships

node.text:
I have been beyond guilty of this in my relationship(s). I love to celebrate my birthday. I love to celebrate pretty much everything (I’m a Leo…). So around my birthday every year I would just kind of expect people to know exactly what I wanted, when, etc.

Inevitably, my husband would ask me “what do you want to do for your birthday?” and I would respond with the exact opposite of what I wanted. “Oh I’m cool with whatever! We can do something casual.”

I was in fact not cool with “whatever” and I expected him to know that.

When we do this the outcome is never good:
The other person is both annoyed and confused.
They don’t know what you want and if they listen to you they might get it wrong and if they don’t…they might also get it wrong.
You end up not getting what you want.
Disappointment and resentment build.

I think many of us are under the impression that our partner should just KNOW what we want and give it to us even when we’re asking for the opposite. (Like me wanting a huge party and saying I’m cool with “whatever”….). It seems somehow less romantic when we have to ask. Or we think they should just “know” us well enough to not listen to what we’re saying or just know what we want without us having to say it.

But you know what isn’t romantic, or cool, or fun?
Being disappointed.
Blaming your partner.
Not getting what you need or want.

Do you struggle with this??

Speaking from personal experience here. These are all things I used to do in certain relationships.

This can happen in so many different types of adult relationships - with parents, partners, friends, etc.

You may have learned that this is how you show that you care by watching other people.
This may be how you’ve kept your role in a certain relationship or secured value.
These behaviors can develop after a trauma or distressing event.
They’re also symptoms of anxiety or worry.

Have you done any of these things?

Do you find yourself or other people in your life showing that they care about you through anxiety or worry?

How does it impact your relationship?

node.text:
Whenever I post about parenting, I get a lot of pushback. I know parenting is very, very hard. There is no such thing as a perfect parent. But, parents often want their kids to understand their side without having to listen to what it was like for the child.

I hear a lot of defensiveness when doing this work.
“You don’t know how hard it was to put food on the table.”
“I was just doing my best.”
“I loved you.”
“You had a better childhood than most.”
These things can all be true, and your adult child may still have their own pain they carry.

When I work with adults who had difficult childhoods, (who want to understand their parents and develop empathy), they almost always develop empathy for their parents throughout the therapy process. It’s not a secret that parents who do harm are usually just passing on what they know. When we understand that story it’s easier to understand.

So many adults want to understand their parents and why they made certain choices. They want to make sense of a childhood that maybe didn’t make sense.

Therapy usually gives people insight and understanding. When this happens, The adults I work with typically see their parents as human and try to understand the behavior.

But, if they’re going to empathize with their parents, adult children need their perspective to be validated, too. when parents refuse to acknowledge their role or take responsibility, it can be traumatic. It inhibits connection and empathy. 

***THIS IS NOT AN EXCUSE FOR ABUSE. If understanding and empathizing with your parents isn’t helpful and/or you don’t want to, you do not have to. If you are in that place, this post likely does not apply to you***

node.text:
Until recently, I believed that if I just tried a little bit harder, I could get someone to like me or understand me.

There are so many amazing communication skills and tactics being shared out there. But it can also keep you stuck in this cycle of self-improvement that says “If I just work a little bit harder….this relationship will improve or they’ll finally understand me.”

You can do all the work in the world and there will still be people that are committed to misunderstanding you.
There will still be people that don’t agree with you.
There will still be people that deny your reality.

This doesn’t mean we shouldn’t try to learn and improve! But, it’s important to know that sometimes it’s not you. Sometimes you’ve done all the work and you know you tried your hardest.

You know when you’ve done the work. 
Have you read about communicating better?
Have you consulted with any therapists or other “experts”?
Have you been practicing?
Do you have deep relationships with other people?
Have you asked for feedback from other people?
Have you reflected on your role in the situation?
Have you been consistently working on your own inner stuff?

If you’ve practiced the scripts, read the books, consulted with the experts, asked for feedback, etc. and the relationship still isn’t improving…take a pause. Maybe you can see that this pattern isn’t showing up in your other relationships. You’ve reflected on what your part is and taken ownership of it. Is the other person doing this too?

Not every relationship can be improved or fixed. Not every relationship is a two-way street. Sometimes it’s one person doing all the other work.

This is just your friendly reminder that sometimes it’s ok to call it quits. It doesn’t mean you failed. It doesn’t mean you did anything wrong.
